summary.seg: This Gospel book was copied at the end of 15th century by Georgios Hermonymos of Sparta (ca. 1430-ca. 1511). In addition to being a copyist, Hermonymos was also a diplomat (he was sent to England by Pope Sixtus IV) and the first lecturer in Greek at the Collège de Sorbonne in Paris.

Hermonymos also copied:
Cambridge, University Library, MS Kk.6.23
Cambridge, University Library, MS Ll.2.13
Cambridge, University Library, MS Nn.4.2
Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 224
. Kk.5.35 and Ll.2.13 have in common the Gospels and two final texts by Psellus and Gregory of Nazianzus. It is possible that the two manuscripts are related in terms of textual transmission.

support.material: ff. 2r-403v Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: Single-handle pot ( 40 15 ) on the gutter comparable to Briquet 12624-12626 , dated between the end of the 15th century and the beginning of the 16th century.

supportDesc.foliation: [i-ii] + 2-403 + [iii-iv]. Modern foliation in pencil in Arabic numerals, recto, top right. Folio number 1 assigned to leaves no longer present in the volume (as per historic foliation practices at Cambridge University Library).

collation.p:
The manuscript consists of 52 quires, all quaternions except those at the end of Matthew, Luke and John, wich have only four leaves:
Quire 18-1 ff. 2r-8v
Quires 2-158 ff. 9r-120v
Quire 164 ff. 121r-124v
Quire 178 ff. 125r-132v
Quire 188-1 ff. 133r-139v (after f. 137v one folio was cancelled by the scribe)
Quires 19-398 ff. 187r-307v
Quire 404 ff. 308r-311v
Quires 41-518 ff. 312r-399v
Quire 524 ff. 400r-403v
Henry Bradshaw (1831-1886) added a general note on collation on right cover, inner.
collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords in the hand of the scribe placed along the inner bounding line, underlined, reading from top to bottom.
collation.signatures: Original quire signatures in Greek numeral in red ink from αον (f. 8v) to νβον (f. 400r) remain in the middle of the lower margin of recto of the first folio and the verso of the last folio of each quire, except for αον only on the last verso, and νβον only on the first recto.
A leaf signature in Greek numerals in dark brown ink in the lower margin of the rectos, from f. 2r φύλλ. βον τοῦ αου to f. 400r φύλλ. αον τοῦ νβου.

supportDesc.condition: In poor condition. Leaves are lightly yellow with age, there are occasional stains and the paper is slightly worm-eaten. f. 172 is detached and the text block is divide in two parts.

layoutDesc.layout: One column of 14 lines; written space 135-140 80-85

handNote.p: Georgios Hermonymos Hermonymos, Georgios, active 15th century : the four Gospels are written by the 15th-century Greek scholar and scribe (RGK I 61) in a minuscule script in pale brown ink.

Slanting slightly to the right, Hermonymos' hand shows cursive-like ductus without variation in letter size. Ligatures and abbreviations are rare. His script is characterized by the minuscules gamma, eta, xi, rho. Sigma telikon is in Z-shape and is found sometimes in the middle of the word.
Breathings are curved; accents do not join to letters or breathings.
For further details on Georgios Hermonymos' script, see Kalatzi 2009, pp. 111-132.

decoDesc.decoNote: Empty space left for initials of Gospels and a minature on f. 193r which were never executed.
Sample initials of the paragraphs are outlined in red ink.

additions.p: Corrections and translations into Latin of some word have been added by a western hand on ff. 127r, 312r-313v, a manicula on f. 317v, and the final note on f. 403v: Τέλος τῶν δ ευανγελιων (sic)

binding.p:
Couched-laminate board binding covered in quarter mid-brown tanned calfskin with stamped ornamentation and marbled paper on the sides. The title is tooled in gold on the spineEvang. Grec. M.S.. The edges are gilded and gauffred. Left inner joint is partially split, the right inner one is completely split; the rear board is loose. The spine is broken in correspondence with f. 171 and the textblock is divided in two parts.

origin.p: The codex was copied by Georgios Hermonymos in all likelihood during his stay in Paris in the late 15th century.

history.provenance: Owned by John Moore (b. 1646, d. 1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : number 665 of Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697) or, more probably, number 999 of the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL Oo.7.50.2, compiled by Thomas Tanner Tanner, Thomas, 1674-1735 after the publication of Bernard's catalogue. Both classmarks are noted on f. i verso.
history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . The royal bookplate engraved by John Pine (1690-1756) in 1736 remains on the front pastedown.

recordHist.source: Description (2019) draws on A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 3 (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1858, p. 706 and on M.P. Kalatzi, Hermonymos: a study in scribal, literary and teaching activities in the fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries (Cultural Foundation of the National Bank of Greece, 2009), p. 186-187.
